			<div class="content" id="post-content-3784052">
									

<p>Hiring out definitely works better, yes!</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Any other phrasings that stick out to you as particularly egregious?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Well, uh&#8230; ha! Now that you mention it&#8230;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>World War I</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This document is from 1932, so, in the words of David Mitchell, it would be the act of an &quot;incredible pessimist&quot; to call the Great War &quot;World War <em>One</em>&quot;&#8230; xD</p>
<p>I can try to do a comb-over of this at some point tonight if you'd like, but it's not just the lexicographical issues. It's the tone and presentation &#8212; it doesn't sound like something I'd expect a criminal to produce. Where's the alternate spellings? The street grammar? What form did this document exist in &#8212; why does it include photographs? Did this person actually go through the trouble of taking photographs in <em>1932</em>, then label them, and insert them into this note for others to see? Etc.</p>
<p>Sorry if this is coming off as a bit harsh. A document like this is a <em>huge</em> challenge; I appreciate that you just went for it, but I also don't think this really 'recreates' the historical period to which it's supposed to belong.</p>

							</div>

								
					
